{"questionId":"9069455","questionHtml":"<p>Iron(II) is oxidized by bromine.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">2Fe<sup>2+</sup> (aq) + Br<sub>2</sub> (l) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" class=\"wrs_chemistry\"><mo>⇌</mo></math> 2Fe<sup>3+</sup> (aq) + 2Br<sup>−</sup> (aq)</p>\n<p>Calculate the <em>E</em><sup>⦵</sup><sub>cell</sub>, in V, for the reaction using section 24 of the data booklet.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>«<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><msup><mi>E</mi><mo>⦵</mo></msup><mtext>cell</mtext></msub></math>&nbsp;= 1.09 – 0.77 =» 0.32 «V» ✔</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9069455","referenceCode":"22M.2.hl.TZ2.3a(i)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Iron(II) is oxidized by bromine. 2Fe2+ (aq) + Br2 (l) ⇌ 2Fe3+ (aq) + 2Br− (aq) Calculate the E⦵cell, in V, for the reaction using section 24 of the data booklet.","paper":"2","level":"hl","questionNumber":"a(i)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 19: Redox processes","19.1 Electrochemical cells","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 19: Redox processes"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}